        <abstract>
          <p id="P1">Through exomic sequencing of 32 intrahepatic cholangiocarcinomas, we discovered frequent inactivating mutations in multiple chromatin-remodeling genes (including <italic toggle="yes">BAP1</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">ARID1A</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">PBRM1</italic>), and mutation in one of these genes occurred in almost half of the carcinomas sequenced. We also identified frequent mutations at previously reported hotspots in the <italic toggle="yes">IDH1</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">IDH2</italic> genes encoding metabolic enzymes in intrahepatic cholangiocarcinomas. In contrast, <italic toggle="yes">TP53</italic> was the most frequently altered gene in a series of nine gallbladder carcinomas. These discoveries highlight the key role of dysregulated chromatin remodeling in intrahepatic cholangiocarcinomas.</p>
        </abstract>
